    "summary": "1960 is remembered as the Year of Africa because seventeen African countries gained independence from European colonial rule in that single year, representing the most dramatic acceleration of the [[event:114|decolonization of Africa]]. The newly independent states included Nigeria, Senegal, Mali, Ivory Coast, Cameroon, Togo, Madagascar, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Somalia, Benin, Niger, Burkina Faso, Chad, Gabon, the Central African Republic, Mauritania, and others. France granted independence to most of its West and Equatorial African territories, while Belgium relinquished the Congo.\n\nThe year transformed the composition of the United Nations: the seventeen new members nearly doubled the organization's African membership and shifted the General Assembly's balance of power toward newly independent developing nations. The Year of Africa symbolized the collapse of the European colonial order that had dominated the continent since the late nineteenth century. However, independence did not automatically resolve deep structural problems inherited from colonialism, including arbitrary borders, inadequate infrastructure, underdeveloped economies, and inexperienced institutions, challenges that would shape African political history for the remainder of the century.",
